JPMorgan Chase & Co, Wells Fargo Reserved For Mortgage Settlement-DJ
Thursday, 9 Feb 2012 01:05pm EST
Dow Jones reported that JPMorgan Chase & Co and Wells Fargo & Co. have reserved for their respective $5.3 billion share of the settlement big banks reached with the federal government and state attorneys general. The bank has set aside the estimated cost of Thursday's $25 billion settlement in previous quarters. J.P. Morgan's share of the settlement is $5.3 billion, the same as for Wells. Bank of America Corporation is bearing the biggest share, with $11.8 billion; Citigroup Inc. has to pay $2.2 billion, and Ally Financial Inc must pay $310 million. Wells Fargo was financially and operationally prepared for the settlement. In a press release, the Company said it 'had fully accrued' for the following elements of the settlement that impact Wells Fargo; a $900 million refinance program, a $3.4 billion relief program for consumers who experience financial hardship and $1 billion paid to the federal government.Â 
